In "how many people did he live with" question, slightly unsure if that includes him or not.
IN THE 1940'S, THOSE WHO TENDED TO THE LIBRARIES USUALLY LIVED IN THEM.
THIS GUY'S FAMILY LIVED IN THE LIBRARY, AND HIS FATHER WAS THE CUSTODIAN.
HE KEPT THE LIBRARY VERY CLEAN, EVEN WAXING THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES SO THEY WOULD GLEAM.
GROWING UP, THE SON WAS SOMEWHAT ASHAMED OF LIVING IN A LIBRARY, BECAUSE HE WANTED TO BE NORMAL, BUT HE REALIZED THAT HE HAD INFORMATION ABOUT ANYTHING HE THOUGHT OF.
LATE AT NIGHT, HE WOULD SOMETIMES GET CURIOUS ABOUT SOMETHING, AND GO DOWN TO THE LIBRARY TO READ ABOUT IT UNTIL 3AM.
WHEN HE GREW UP, HE TOOK HIS DAD AND SHOWED HIM HIS NAME ON HIS OFFICE DOOR.
HIS DAD LOOKED AT IT, BEING THE SILENT TYPE, BUT HE COULD TELL THAT HE WAS PROUD.
HE HAD WORKED HIS WHOLE LIFE TO GIVE HIS SON SOMETHING BETTER, A GREATER CHANCE TO DO SOMETHING AMAZING.
IN THE 1940'S, THE PEOPLE WHO TENDED TO LIBRARIES USUALLY LIVED IN THEM.
HE TOLD HIS FATHER, "I'M GLAD WE'RE RICH!
" HIS FATHER LAUGHED, AND THEY EXPLAINED THAT THEY WERE ACTUALLY POOR.
HIS DAD WORKED AS A CUSTODIAN IN THE LIBRARY, AND ALWAYS KEPT IT CLEAN.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES, SO THEY WOULD GLEAM.
THE SON NEVER INVITED ANYONE TO HIS HOUSE, SINCE IT WAS DIFFERENT AND HE WANTED TO BE NORMAL.
DURING THE DAY HE HAD TO BE QUIET, BUT AFTER EVERYONE LEFT HE COULD RUN AROUND THE LIBRARY.
LATE AT NIGHT, HE WOULD BE CURIOUS ABOUT SOMETHING, SO HE WOULD GO DOWN TO THE LIBRARY AND READ UNTIL 3AM.
WHEN HE GREW UP, HE TOOK HIS FATHER TO HIS OFFICE.
HE SHOWED HIS FATHER HIS NAME ON THE DOOR, AND HIS FATHER WAS QUIET.
HE WAS PROUD OF HIS SON FOR ACCOMPLISHING SO MUCH, AND THE KNOWLEDGE HIS SON GAINED FROM LIVING IN A LIBRARY.
